        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1970-10-16T16:35:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1970-10-16T15:47:00-05:00" n="52"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d52">
                <head>52. Summary of Conclusions of a Meeting of the Washington Special Actions
                        Group<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d52fn1">Source: National Archives,
                            <persName corresp="#p_NRM1">Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials,
                            <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> Institutional Files (H-Files), Box H–114, <gloss
                            target="#t_WSAG1">WSAG</gloss> Meetings Minutes, Originals, 1969–1970.
                        Top Secret; <gloss target="#t_Nodis1">Nodis</gloss>. The meeting took place
                        in the Situation Room of the White House.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            from="1970-10-16T16:47:00-04:00" to="1970-10-16T17:35:00-04:00">October
                            16, 1970, 4:47–5:35 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Cambodia</item>
                </list>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PARTICIPATION</head>
                    <item>Chairman—<persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Henry A. Kissinger</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>State—Under Secretary <persName corresp="#p_IJN1">John Irwin</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_JUA1">U. Alexis Johnson</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_WJM1">James Wilson</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Defense—Mr. <persName corresp="#p_PD1">David Packard</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_NGW1">G. Warren Nutter</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Rear Adm. <persName corresp="#p_FWR1">William R. Flanagan</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_CIA1">CIA</gloss>—Lt. Gen. <persName corresp="#p_CRE1">R.
                            E. Cushman</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_KTH1">Thomas Karamessines</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName>William Wells</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_JCS1">JCS</gloss>—Adm. <persName corresp="#p_MTH1">Thomas
                            H. Moorer</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>B/Gen. <persName>Robert P. Lukeman</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Gen. <persName corresp="#p_ZM1">Melvin Zais</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_OMB1">OMB</gloss>—Mr. <persName corresp="#p_SJ1">James
                            Schlesinger</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>
                        <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Staff—Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HJH1"
                            >John H. Holdridge</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Col. <persName corresp="#p_KRT1">Richard T. Kennedy</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName>D. Keith Guthrie</persName>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p rend="center">SUMMARY OF CONCLUSIONS</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>The <gloss target="#t_WSAG1">WSAG</gloss> reviewed [<hi rend="italic">less
                            than 1 line not declassified</hi>] plans for employment of Thai Special
                        Guerrilla Units in northern and southern Laos and <gloss
                            target="#t_KhmerKrom1">Khmer Krom</gloss> units in Cambodia.<note n="2"
                            xml:id="d52fn2">In an October 16 memorandum to <persName
                                corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_JUA1"
                                >Johnson</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_PD1">Packard</persName>,
                            and <persName corresp="#p_MTH1">Moorer</persName> on funding Cambodian
                            operations under the <persName corresp="#p_FJW2">Fulbright</persName>
                            Amendment to the Defense Procurement Act, which was enacted on October 7
                            and prohibited funds slated for the <gloss target="#t_GVN1">GVN</gloss>
                            or Thailand to go to Cambodia, [<hi rend="italic">text not
                                declassified</hi>] and that the Defense Department fund Thai,
                            Cambodian, and Lao <gloss target="#t_SGU1">SGU</gloss>s in central and
                            south Laos. (Ibid., Box H–76, <gloss target="#t_WSAG1">WSAG</gloss>
                            Meeting, Cambodia, 10/16/70)</note> The consensus was that these
                        activities should continue to be justified to Congress on the basis that
                        they constituted a continuation of programs already under way and that they
                        served to protect US troops in Vietnam by attacking enemy supply lines and
                        sanctuaries. The <gloss target="#t_WSAG1">WSAG</gloss> endorsed a State
                        Department proposal to instruct Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_SEC1"
                            >Swank</persName> to inform <persName corresp="#p_LN1">Lon
                            Nol</persName> that the <gloss target="#t_KhmerKrom1">Khmer Krom</gloss>
                        units were to be used against enemy sanctuaries and lines of communications.
                        This would serve to place on the record the US intent in supporting the
                            <gloss target="#t_KhmerKrom1">Khmer Krom</gloss> operations.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>The <gloss target="#t_WSAG1">WSAG</gloss> agreed in principle to the
                        proposal to replace Thai regular units in Long Tieng with <gloss
                            target="#t_SGU1">SGU</gloss>s. However, <gloss target="#t_CIA1"
                            >CIA</gloss> and Defense are to provide an analysis of why the
                        substitution of <gloss target="#t_SGU1">SGU</gloss>s will not degrade <pb
                            facs="0172" n="133" xml:id="pg_133"/> friendly military capabilities in
                        Northern Laos.<note n="3" xml:id="d52fn3">
                            <persName corresp="#p_LMR1">Laird</persName> forwarded the study to
                                <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> under a November 3
                            memorandum which recommended that the substitution proceed for political
                            and budgetary reasons even though the <gloss target="#t_SGU1"
                                >SGU</gloss>s would initially be less effective. <persName
                                corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> responded on November 27 that
                            the recruitment and training of the <gloss target="#t_SGU1">SGU</gloss>s
                            should proceed and their effectiveness be reevaluated toward the end of
                            March 1971. Both documents are attached to a memorandum from <persName
                                corresp="#p_HJH1">Holdridge</persName> and <persName
                                corresp="#p_KRT1">Kennedy</persName> to <persName corresp="#p_KHA1"
                                >Kissinger</persName>, November 23. (Ibid., Box 548, Country Files,
                            Far East, Laos, Vol. VI)</note> Differences in armament and equipment
                        between the regular Thai units and the <gloss target="#t_SGU1">SGU</gloss>s
                        will be specified. In addition, State will request Ambassador <persName
                            corresp="#p_GGM1">Godley</persName>’s judgment on the desirability and
                        timing of phasing the <gloss target="#t_SGU1">SGU</gloss>s into Long
                        Tieng.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Defense will coordinate preparation of an inter-agency paper setting forth
                        the advantages and disadvantages of providing an M–16 factory to Indonesia
                        in return for Indonesian assistance in supplying AK–47 weapons and
                        ammunition to Cambodia. Arrangements made to pay Indonesia for ammunition
                        supplied to Cambodia should provide generous compensation without, however,
                        accepting unreasonable Indonesia prices.<note n="4" xml:id="d52fn4">In a
                            memorandum to <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>, October
                            27, <persName corresp="#p_PD1">Packard</persName> indicated that the
                            plans for the M–16 factory would not be economically practical.
                                <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> responded with a
                            memorandum to <persName corresp="#p_PD1">Packard</persName>, November 2,
                            asking for a fuller study of the factory option. (Ibid., <gloss
                                target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Institutional Files (H-Files), Box
                            H–76, <gloss target="#t_WSAG1">WSAG</gloss> Meeting, Cambodia,
                            10/16/70)</note>
                    </item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>The <gloss target="#t_WSAG1">WSAG</gloss> was reminded that in considering
                        the question of Thai military involvement in Cambodia, the President’s deep
                        interest in insuring that all feasible measures be taken to provide for the
                        defense of Cambodia must be taken into account. In this connection, it is
                        essential to obtain as soon as possible Thai agreement to contingency plans
                        for employment of Thai ground and air forces in Cambodia as required;
                        economic assistance trade-offs should be offered to the Thais to enlist
                        their cooperation. The State Department will insure that Ambassador Unger is
                        informed of the above considerations.<note n="5" xml:id="d52fn5">Unger was
                            informed in telegram 172147 to Bangkok, October 19. (Ibid., <gloss
                                target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1970–73, <gloss
                                target="#t_POL1">POL</gloss> 27 LAOS) <persName corresp="#p_KHA1"
                                >Kissinger</persName> also sent a letter to Unger on the issue,
                            October 27; see <ref target="frus1969-76v20#d95">
                                <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1969–1976, volume XX,
                                Southeast Asia, 1969–1972, Document 95</ref>.</note>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>[Omitted here are the minutes of the meeting.]</p>
            </div>
